Real-Time Data Streaming with Apache Kafka
Prerequisites
Basic Linux command-line knowledge
Understanding of terminal operations
Familiarity with basic networking concepts (ports, localhost)
Java basics (Kafka runs on JVM)
Learning Objectives
By completing this lab, you will:

Install and configure Apache Kafka on a Linux machine
Create and manage Kafka topics
Produce messages to Kafka topics in real-time
Consume messages from Kafka topics
Understand basic pub-sub messaging patterns
Environment Setup
System Requirements
Linux machine (provided via "Start Lab" button)
Minimum 2GB RAM
Internet connection for downloading packages
Install Java
# Update package manager
sudo apt update

# Install OpenJDK 11
sudo apt install -y openjdk-11-jdk

# Verify installation
java -version
Download and Install Kafka
# Navigate to home directory
cd ~

# Download Kafka (version 3.6.0)
wget https://downloads.apache.org/kafka/3.6.0/kafka_2.13-3.6.0.tgz

# Extract the archive
tar -xzf kafka_2.13-3.6.0.tgz

# Rename for convenience
mv kafka_2.13-3.6.0 kafka

# Navigate to Kafka directory
cd kafka
Start Kafka Services
Kafka requires ZooKeeper to run. Start both services in separate terminal sessions.

Terminal 1 - Start ZooKeeper:

cd ~/kafka
bin/zookeeper-server-start.sh config/zookeeper.properties
Terminal 2 - Start Kafka Broker:

cd ~/kafka
bin/kafka-server-start.sh config/server.properties
Keep both terminals running. Open a new terminal (Terminal 3) for the remaining tasks.

Task 1: Create and Manage Kafka Topics
Step 1: Create a Topic
cd ~/kafka

# Create a topic named 'user-events'
bin/kafka-topics.sh --create \
  --topic user-events \
  --bootstrap-server localhost:9092 \
  --partitions 3 \
  --replication-factor 1
Parameters explained:

--topic: Name of the topic
--bootstrap-server: Kafka broker address
--partitions: Number of partitions for parallel processing
--replication-factor: Number of replicas (1 for single broker)
Step 2: List Topics
# View all topics
bin/kafka-topics.sh --list --bootstrap-server localhost:9092
Step 3: Describe Topic Details
# Get detailed information about the topic
bin/kafka-topics.sh --describe \
  --topic user-events \
  --bootstrap-server localhost:9092
Expected Output:

Topic name, partition count, replication factor
Leader and replica information for each partition
Task 2: Produce Messages to Kafka
Step 1: Start Console Producer
Open Terminal 4 for the producer:

cd ~/kafka

# Start interactive producer
bin/kafka-console-producer.sh \
  --topic user-events \
  --bootstrap-server localhost:9092
Step 2: Send Messages
Type messages directly in the terminal. Each line is a separate message:

{"user_id": 101, "action": "login", "timestamp": "2024-01-15T10:30:00"}
{"user_id": 102, "action": "page_view", "timestamp": "2024-01-15T10:31:00"}
{"user_id": 101, "action": "purchase", "timestamp": "2024-01-15T10:32:00"}
{"user_id": 103, "action": "logout", "timestamp": "2024-01-15T10:33:00"}
Press Enter after each message. Keep this terminal open.

Step 3: Producer with Key-Value Pairs
Stop the previous producer (Ctrl+C) and start a new one with keys:

bin/kafka-console-producer.sh \
  --topic user-events \
  --bootstrap-server localhost:9092 \
  --property "parse.key=true" \
  --property "key.separator=:"
Send messages with keys:

user101:{"action": "login", "timestamp": "2024-01-15T10:35:00"}
user102:{"action": "signup", "timestamp": "2024-01-15T10:36:00"}
Keys ensure messages from the same user go to the same partition.

Task 3: Consume Messages from Kafka
Step 1: Start Console Consumer
Open Terminal 5 for the consumer:

cd ~/kafka

# Consume messages from the beginning
bin/kafka-console-consumer.sh \
  --topic user-events \
  --bootstrap-server localhost:9092 \
  --from-beginning
You should see all previously produced messages.

Step 2: Real-Time Consumption
Stop the consumer (Ctrl+C) and restart without --from-beginning:

bin/kafka-console-consumer.sh \
  --topic user-events \
  --bootstrap-server localhost:9092
Now switch to Terminal 4 (producer) and send new messages. Watch them appear in Terminal 5 in real-time.

Step 3: Consumer Groups
Stop the previous consumer and start with a consumer group:

bin/kafka-console-consumer.sh \
  --topic user-events \
  --bootstrap-server localhost:9092 \
  --group analytics-group \
  --from-beginning
Consumer groups enable:

Load balancing across multiple consumers
Offset tracking (remembers last read position)
Fault tolerance
Step 4: Multiple Consumers in Same Group
Open Terminal 6 and start another consumer in the same group:

cd ~/kafka

bin/kafka-console-consumer.sh \
  --topic user-events \
  --bootstrap-server localhost:9092 \
  --group analytics-group
Send messages from the producer. Notice how messages are distributed between the two consumers (load balancing).

Step 5: View Consumer Group Details
In a new terminal:

cd ~/kafka

# List all consumer groups
bin/kafka-consumer-groups.sh \
  --bootstrap-server localhost:9092 \
  --list

# Describe specific group
bin/kafka-consumer-groups.sh \
  --bootstrap-server localhost:9092 \
  --group analytics-group \
  --describe
Output shows:

Current offset (last read message)
Log end offset (total messages)
Lag (unread messages)
Consumer ID and host
Verification
Verify Topic Creation
cd ~/kafka

# Check topic exists
bin/kafka-topics.sh --list --bootstrap-server localhost:9092 | grep user-events

# Verify configuration
bin/kafka-topics.sh --describe --topic user-events --bootstrap-server localhost:9092
Expected: Topic listed with 3 partitions, replication factor 1.

Verify Message Production
# Count messages in topic
bin/kafka-run-class.sh kafka.tools.GetOffsetShell \
  --broker-list localhost:9092 \
  --topic user-events
Expected: Non-zero offset values indicating messages were produced.

Verify Message Consumption
# Check consumer group lag
bin/kafka-consumer-groups.sh \
  --bootstrap-server localhost:9092 \
  --group analytics-group \
  --describe
Expected: LAG column shows 0 or low numbers, indicating messages were consumed.

End-to-End Test
Start a consumer in one terminal
Send a test message from producer: {"test": "verification"}
Confirm message appears in consumer terminal within 1-2 seconds
Troubleshooting
Kafka Won't Start
Issue: Port 9092 already in use

# Check if Kafka is already running
ps aux | grep kafka

# Kill existing processes
pkill -f kafka
ZooKeeper Connection Error
Issue: Kafka can't connect to ZooKeeper

# Verify ZooKeeper is running on port 2181
netstat -tuln | grep 2181

# Restart ZooKeeper if needed
cd ~/kafka
bin/zookeeper-server-start.sh config/zookeeper.properties
Messages Not Appearing
Issue: Consumer not receiving messages

Verify topic name matches exactly (case-sensitive)
Check producer terminal for errors
Ensure bootstrap-server is localhost:9092
Try --from-beginning flag on consumer
Out of Memory Error
# Reduce Kafka heap size
export KAFKA_HEAP_OPTS="-Xmx512M -Xms512M"

# Restart Kafka broker
Cleanup
Stop Services Gracefully
# Stop consumers and producers (Ctrl+C in respective terminals)

# Stop Kafka broker
cd ~/kafka
bin/kafka-server-stop.sh

# Stop ZooKeeper
bin/zookeeper-server-stop.sh
Delete Topic (Optional)
bin/kafka-topics.sh --delete \
  --topic user-events \
  --bootstrap-server localhost:9092
